{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aa6e9626-165c-40a1-837e-0901c0c3871c","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n1. **User-level crashes:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level crashes:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**Quick way to find it:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\n**You can also use Console.app** → sidebar → \"Crash Reports\" to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For a core dump** (full memory dump), macOS disables them by default. To enable:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nThen reproduce the crash — the core file lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n> 💡 If you need help symbolicating the `.ips` crash log to resolve .NET runtime frames, let me know — I can walk you through that too.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9746086e-2854-48fb-8530-eb59530a1fb3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a diagnostic question — let me answer directly from my knowledge.","outputTokens":345,"requestId":"D7C0:1BB519:1C69BD:213EBE:69F2B4E7"},"id":"2b2a0400-f3bb-4257-8b47-32558a2eef04","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:48:32.429Z","parentId":"8e99ee0b-4821-41ce-b108-e571b57d4bf8"}
